---
import BaseLayout from "@layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout title="About" lang="en" path="/en/about/">
  <section class="about">
    <div class="about__container">
      <h1>About Seishinkai</h1>

      <div class="about__introduction">
        <p>
          Seishinkai is Hokkaido’s first non-profit karate organization,
          officially incorporated in February 2004 with approval from the
          Governor of Hokkaido.
        </p>

        <p>
          It was established on the foundation of the Seishinkan Okubo Dojo,
          founded in 1986 after the passing of the first Soke, and traces its
          roots back to the original Seishin-ryu Karate Sapporo Branch founded
          in 1976 under Branch Chief Katsumi Okubo.
        </p>

        <p>
          Official registered name: Specified Nonprofit Corporation All Japan
          Seishinkai
        </p>

        <p>
          Main activities: Karate instruction, international cultural exchange,
          and support programs for international karate students.
        </p>

        <p>
          We also offer long-term and short-term training opportunities for
          international students, trial karate experiences, and Iaido
          experiences for overseas visitors.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="about__timeline">
        <h2>History</h2>
        <div class="accordion">

          <div class="accordion__item">
            <button class="accordion__button" data-accordion-trigger="item1">
              <span>Founding & Foundation Building (1957–1986)</span>
              <svg class="accordion__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
                <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline>
              </svg>
            </button>
            <div class="accordion__panel" data-accordion-panel="item1">
              <div class="accordion__content about__timeline-content">
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <span class="about__timeline-date">1957</span>
                    Seishin-ryu was founded in Mita, Tokyo by Soke Kazuo Kikuchi
                    (Karate, Iaido, Jujutsu, and Jojutsu)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <span class="about__timeline-date">1976</span>
                    Established as the Seishin-ryu Sapporo Branch<br>
                    (Katsumi Okubo appointed branch chief by Soke Kazuo Kikuchi)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <span class="about__timeline-date">1983</span>
                    Passing of founder Soke Kazuo Kikuchi
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <span class="about__timeline-date">1986</span>
                    Seishinkan Okubo Dojo (Seishin-ryu Okubo Branch) established
                    with the support of Supporters’ Association Chairman Yoshihiko Watanabe
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="accordion__item">
            <button class="accordion__button" data-accordion-trigger="item2">
              <span>Development & Expansion Across Hokkaido (1987–2003)</span>
              <svg class="accordion__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
                <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline>
              </svg>
            </button>
            <div class="accordion__panel" data-accordion-panel="item2">
              <div class="accordion__content about__timeline-content">
                <ul>
                  <li><span class="about__timeline-date">1987</span> First Seishinkai Karate Tournament held</li>
                  <li><span class="about__timeline-date">1990</span> Sapporo East Branch established with support from San-ai Motor Industry</li>
                  <li><span class="about__timeline-date">1992</span> Hokuto Branch established with support from Alumni Chairman Masami Koyano</li>
                  <li><span class="about__timeline-date">1993–</span> Atsubetsu, Asabu, Tsukisamu, Okushiri Island and other regional branches established</li>
                  <li><span class="about__timeline-date">1995</span> Official Seishinkan website launched</li>
                  <li><span class="about__timeline-date">2000</span> Internet Karate School launched</li>
                  <li>
                    <span class="about__timeline-date">2002</span>
                    Yamanashi Branch (Minobusan University Karate Club) and Shizuoka Branch established<br>
                    Headquarters relocated to Higashi-Sapporo
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <span class="about__timeline-date">2003</span>
                    Surpassed 20 branches and submitted NPO certification application to the Governor of Hokkaido
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="accordion__item">
            <button class="accordion__button" data-accordion-trigger="item3">
              <span>Incorporation & National Organization Growth (2004–2011)</span>
              <svg class="accordion__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
                <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline>
              </svg>
            </button>
            <div class="accordion__panel" data-accordion-panel="item3">
              <div class="accordion__content about__timeline-content">
                <ul>
                  <li><span class="about__timeline-date">2004</span> Officially registered as the Specified Nonprofit Corporation “All Japan Seishinkai”</li>
                  <li>
                    <span class="about__timeline-date">2005</span>
                    Hayakita Branch (Seishinkan Takahashi Dojo) joined<br>
                    Headquarters relocated to Shiroishi Seishinkan; Iaido Division established
                  </li>
                  <li><span class="about__timeline-date">2006</span> Niikappu Hokushinkai joined</li>
                  <li><span class="about__timeline-date">2007</span> Kimobetsu Branch established; short-term international student program began</li>
                  <li><span class="about__timeline-date">2008</span> Muryujuku (Chiba Prefecture) joined</li>
                  <li><span class="about__timeline-date">2009</span> Surpassed 70 branches; All Japan Seishinkai Karate Federation established</li>
                  <li><span class="about__timeline-date">2010</span> Permanent Oasa Seishinkan dojo established; full-scale live-in karate student program began</li>
                  <li><span class="about__timeline-date">2011</span> First overseas branch established in Sri Lanka; Hondori Seishinkan opened</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="accordion__item">
            <button class="accordion__button" data-accordion-trigger="item4">
              <span>International Expansion & Major Growth (2012–2019)</span>
              <svg class="accordion__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
                <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline>
              </svg>
            </button>
            <div class="accordion__panel" data-accordion-panel="item4">
              <div class="accordion__content about__timeline-content">
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <span class="about__timeline-date">2012</span>
                    Surpassed 120 domestic and international branches; ISKF established<br>
                    Trademark registration of Seishin-ryu Karate, Seishinkai, and logo<br>
                    Headquarters dojo opened in Shiroishi Ward<br>
                    Hokkaido’s first female dojo director appointed
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <span class="about__timeline-date">2013</span>
                    Fukuoka Branch established; expansion into India and other overseas locations<br>
                    Annual international instructor exchanges began
                  </li>
                  <li><span class="about__timeline-date">2014</span> Seishinkan Yamamoto Training Center established</li>
                  <li><span class="about__timeline-date">2015</span> Official style name adopted as “Seishin-ryu Kenpo Karate”</li>
                  <li><span class="about__timeline-date">2016</span> Seishinkai Memorial Monument established; Chuo Higashi Dojo opened</li>
                  <li><span class="about__timeline-date">2017</span> New branches established in Kyogoku and Ishikari Ryokuendai</li>
                  <li><span class="about__timeline-date">2018</span> Hondori Seishinkan renovated and expanded; new Acacia, Nango, and Chuo South branches opened</li>
                  <li><span class="about__timeline-date">2019</span> Makomanai and Pakistan branches established</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="accordion__item">
            <button class="accordion__button" data-accordion-trigger="item5">
              <span>Succession & Modern Development (2020–Present)</span>
              <svg class="accordion__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
                <polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline>
              </svg>
            </button>
            <div class="accordion__panel" data-accordion-panel="item5">
              <div class="accordion__content about__timeline-content">
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <span class="about__timeline-date">2020</span>
                    Full-scale online karate classes launched in response to COVID-19<br>
                    Bangladesh and Nepal branches established<br>
                    Tsubasa Okubo succeeded as Head of Headquarters and second-generation ISKF Soke
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <span class="about__timeline-date">2021</span>
                    Health movement exercise classes launched<br>
                    Website surpassed 1.5 million visitors<br>
                    Membership exceeded 7,000
                  </li>
                  <li><span class="about__timeline-date">2022</span> Total cumulative membership reached 7,444</li>
                  <li><span class="about__timeline-date">2023</span> Inoue Dojo completed; Sweden training expedition; Hamatonbetsu Branch established</li>
                  <li><span class="about__timeline-date">2024</span> Australia Branch established</li>
                  <li><span class="about__timeline-date">2025</span> Membership surpassed 8,000; Argentina Branch and Toyota Study Group established</li>
                  <li><span class="about__timeline-date">2026</span> New Zealand Branch established; 62 overseas dojos and approximately 2,700 overseas members</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <h2>Organization Information</h2>
      <table class="about__info-table table">
        <tr>
          <th>Organization Name</th>
          <td>
            Seishinkai<br />
            *The name "Seishin-ryu Karate Seishinkai" and its logo are officially
            trademark registered.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>Style Name</th>
          <td>Seishin-ryu Kenpo Karate (Okubo Branch)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>Dojo Name</th>
          <td>
            Permanent headquarters dojos operate under the name "Seishinkan"
            (regional branches use "[Region Name] Seishinkan").
            Headquarters and affiliated dojos include:
            Sakaedori Seishinkan, Shiroishi Seishinkan, Hondori Seishinkan,
            Oasa Seishinkan, and Seishinkan Yamamoto Training Center.
            Authorized dojos:
            Sumiyoshi-juku, Inoue Dojo, Hokureikai (Misawa Temple Dojo)
            Affiliated dojos:
            Seishinkan Takahashi Dojo, Hokushinkai
            Cooperative partner dojos:
            Aozorakai, Muryujuku
            Only dojos listed in our official dojo directory are recognized as
            official branches, clubs, and affiliated training locations.
          </td>
        </tr>
      </table>
      <h2>Seishin-ryu Kenpo Karate ISKF</h2>
      <table class="about__info-table table">
        <tr>
          <th>Origins</th>
          <td>
            Seishin-ryu Kenpo Karate was developed by Katsumi Okubo, former head of the
            Seishin-ryu Sapporo Branch, drawing from his experience in traditional dojo
            training, university karate clubs, Okinawan kobudo, Japan Self-Defense Force
            hand-to-hand combat, and jujutsu.

            The style was strongly influenced by the late Professor Yoichi Muroki of
            Hokkaido University, a specialist in developmental science and exercise
            physiology, with emphasis placed on health-oriented and educational karate.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>Kata</th>
          <td>
            Basic Defensive Kata, Ho-kei (4), Taikyoku (3), Pinan (5),
            Tai Sabaki (3), Naifanchin, Seiryu, Passai, Seisan,
            Kusanku, Shinpa, Wanshu, and others
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>Kumite</th>
          <td>
            9 basic pre-arranged sparring forms, single-step kumite,
            multi-step kumite, bunkai kumite, and Kumite Kata I & II
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>Kobudo</th>
          <td>
            Sai, Tonfa, Iaido weapon techniques, and self-defense jujutsu
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>Competition</th>
          <td>
            Official competitions use protective equipment rules.
            Branches are also free to participate independently in
            JKF-style point sparring or full-contact competition organizations.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>Emblem</th>
          <td>
            <div class="u-col about__images">
              <div class="about__image-case">
                <div class="about__image-case-set">
                  <img src="/seishinkai/assets/images/img_wappen_01.jpg" alt="" />
                  <small>8cm Diameter Patch</small>
                </div>
                <div class="about__image-case-set">
                  <img src="/seishinkai/assets/images/img_wappen_02.jpg" alt="" />
                  <small>5cm × 6.5cm Sleeve Patch</small>
                </div>
                <div class="about__image-case-set">
                  <div class="u-row">
                    <img src="/seishinkai/assets/images/img_wappen_03.jpg" alt="" />
                    <img src="/seishinkai/assets/images/img_wappen_04.jpg" alt="" />
                  </div>
                  <small>Chest Embroidery</small>
                </div>
              </div>
              <small>
                Some authorized dojos also feature
                embroidered dojo names.
              </small>
              <small>
                *The logo shown on the left
                is trademark registered.
              </small>

                Some organizations originating from old Seishin-ryu groups may use similar
                logos, but unless listed in our official branch directory they are separate
                organizations and not affiliated with us.
                Our trademark has been officially registered since 2012.

            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>Karate Uniform</th>
          <td>
            Official original-design karate uniform with custom construction
            distinct from commercially available uniforms.

            Available through Fujido Sports and Toyo Budogu.
          </td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
